<p>Making good word choices has nothing whatsoever to do with how many words you have to choose from or how many possible combinations there are.Â  Words are not random elements at all.Â  Every time you choose a word, you bring along its meaning(s), all the related grammar, its connotations, its likely bedfellows, its history, cultural information, and lots of unspoken assumptions grounded in shared human experience.Â  When you choose a word, you pull on the leaf, but you also pull on the branch.Â  You can also think of this as a chess move.Â  Choosing any word commits you to a course of action, opening up some options, but also closing off others.</p>

<p>Your word choices should be just as strategic and purposeful as the chess moves you make.Â  If they are not, they detract from the quality of your writing, making it ill-focused and hard to understand.</p>

